******
[2]
Date: Wed 24 Jul 2013
Source: Toronto Star [edited]
http://www.thestar.com/life/health_wellness/2013/07/24/toronto_sees_spike_in_legionnaires_disease_cases.html


Toronto [Ontario province] has had 5 times as many cases of legionnaires' disease in the past 6 weeks as it did last year [2012], according to public health officials. From the beginning of June [2013] to [19 Jul 2013], there were 16 reported cases of the disease in the city. "We've investigated (our cases) and we haven't found any common link. They're not clustered in one area of the city or have been linked to a common exposure. So it's really hard to say why the increase is occurring," said Dr Rita Shahin, one of the city's associate medical officers of health.

There is typically an increase in cases of the disease in August, but this year [2013] it has occurred earlier than usual. Officials are baffled about why exactly it moved up and what the future holds. "What we don't know is, has the increase just moved up in time this summer or are we going to see more cases in August?" said Shahin. "It's really hard to say what's going to happen."

Numbers for the disease province-wide are higher than the 5-year average, according to Dr Doug Sider, medical director of communicable disease prevention and control at Public Health Ontario. Between [1 Jun 2013] and [16 Jul 2013] there were 43 confirmed cases of legionnaires' [disease] across the province.

"There are so many factors that can lead to exposure to legionella bacteria that we need to understand, actively investigate and try to piece together and learn from the cases that are occurring," said Sider. Dr Michael Gardam, an infectious disease expert with University Health Network, says rates of legionnaires' disease have steadily increased in North America and Europe for the past decade. "It's one of those things that we measure that we notice is increasing, and it's not like other diseases where it's confined to one geographic area or confined to risky behaviour that you can say, 'Well, if you stop doing that, you won't get it,'" said Gardam. He noted one possible factor for the rise is increased awareness and testing for the disease in those who present with pneumonia-like symptoms.

The disease typically affects older people and those with compromised immune systems. Symptoms include high fever, chills, a cough and muscle pain, according to Toronto Public Health. It is treatable with antibiotics but can be fatal in people with pre-existing health problems, especially the elderly and those with compromised immune systems. The bacterium that causes it, _Legionella pneumophila_, thrives in stagnant water, according to Shahin.

"I've seen some speculation that (the increase in Toronto) may have had to do with the delayed onset of the hot weather and water stagnating in air conditioning units and water towers," said Shahin. Legionnaires' doesn't spread person-to-person, she said, but is acquired through bacteria that can grow in hot tubs, cooling towers or air conditioning units. "It is a fairly common bacteria, but really, if people have air conditioning units or humidifiers or dehumidifiers it's really not letting water pool there for long periods of time," said Shahin.

Last year [2012], 180 people were infected in a legionnaires' [disease] outbreak in Quebec -- 13 people died. In 2005, 23 seniors died at a Toronto nursing home after an outbreak of legionnaires' disease.

[byline: Tim Alamenciak]

