[Legionnaires' disease is rarely confirmed with laboratory testing because most cases of community-acquired pneumonia are treated empirically without identifying the causative pathogen. In addition, when legionnaires' disease is suspected, the legionella urinary antigen assay is often used to confirm the diagnosis. Because the urine antigen detects only _L. pneumophila_ serogroup 1, legionnaires' disease due to _Legionella_ species other than _L. pneumophila_ or non-serogroup 1 _L. pneumophila_ species will be missed. Therefore, analyzing only reported cases of legionnaires' disease will severely underestimate the burden of this disease.

An increase in cases of legionnaires' disease has also been noted in the US (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6228md.htm?s_cid=mm6228md_w#fig1). The increase is occurring mainly in Mid-Atlantic states (New Jersey, New York, and Pennsylvania; 37 per cent increase), East North Central states (Illinois, Indiana, and Ohio; 43 per cent increase), South Atlantic states (Florida, Maryland, North Carolina, and Virginia; 17 per cent increase), and Pacific states (California and Washington; 33 per cent increase) (Table 2, http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6228md.htm?s_cid=mm6228md_w#tab2). The reason(s) for this increase in the incidence of legionellosis this year [2013] is unknown. For a discussion of this matter, see ProMED-mail post Legionellosis - USA (04): (WI) increased incidence 20130723.1841434.

A map of Ontario showing the location of Toronto can be accessed at http://www.canada-maps.org/ontario-map.htm. The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Canada is available at http://healthmap.org/r/1*Y3. - Mod.ML]
